{"type":"message_update","assistantMessageEvent":{"type":"toolcall_end","contentIndex":1,"toolCall":{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7df9c03eb22c48ce8bffba53","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The operation was fundamentally a special operations raid to capture Maduro, which falls under the carve-out for 'capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO'. The admitted record shows U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela for approximately two hours to apprehend Maduro, not to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government with lasting effect as defined in the proposition, or establish operational control of a major population center.\"}"}},"partial":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on the opportunity information, I can see that I have a deliberation opportunity ready for the AAR case. I've received the prompt and have access to the arbitration record consisting of openings, arguments, rebuttals, surrebuttals, closings, and evidence from both plaintiff and defendant.\n\nLet me review the key components of the record to determine the appropriate vote:\n\nThe proposition is whether \"The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.\"\n\nThe evidence shows:\n- PX-1 (War.gov/Defense) describes a military operation with ground forces in Caracas that captured Maduro  \n- PX-2 (White House/Rubio) confirms ground forces were present for about two hours for the capture\n- The operation was described as \"not an invasion or extended military operation\"\n- The Defense source states Maduro was \"now out of power\" and US would \"oversee Venezuela\"\n- The event happened on Jan 3, 2026, well before the expiration date\n\nWhile U.S. ground forces did enter Venezuelan territory in combat capacity and achieved the capture of Maduro, the official statements indicate the operation was primarily for capture and extraction (\"joint military and law enforcement raid\") rather than a sustained effort to seize/hold territory, or establish control of a major population center. The evidence weighs toward this being more of a special operations raid focused on capturing an individual leader, rather than removing the sitting government in the broader sense meant by the proposition, despite the language about overseeing Venezuela post-operation.\n\nBased on the specific carve-out in the proposition that \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO\" and the admitted evidence showing this was primarily a short-term capture operation without indication of lasting territorial control or occupation, I'm submitting my vote.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7df9c03eb22c48ce8bffba53","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The operation was fundamentally a special operations raid to capture Maduro, which falls under the carve-out for 'capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO'. The admitted record shows U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela for approximately two hours to apprehend Maduro, not to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government with lasting effect as defined in the proposition, or establish operational control of a major population center.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-coder-plus","usage":{"input":16161,"output":510,"cacheRead":2560,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19231,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782786507902,"responseId":"gen-1782786508-mndgv8ljcTcj7yUNSfLn"}},"message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on the opportunity information, I can see that I have a deliberation opportunity ready for the AAR case. I've received the prompt and have access to the arbitration record consisting of openings, arguments, rebuttals, surrebuttals, closings, and evidence from both plaintiff and defendant.\n\nLet me review the key components of the record to determine the appropriate vote:\n\nThe proposition is whether \"The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.\"\n\nThe evidence shows:\n- PX-1 (War.gov/Defense) describes a military operation with ground forces in Caracas that captured Maduro  \n- PX-2 (White House/Rubio) confirms ground forces were present for about two hours for the capture\n- The operation was described as \"not an invasion or extended military operation\"\n- The Defense source states Maduro was \"now out of power\" and US would \"oversee Venezuela\"\n- The event happened on Jan 3, 2026, well before the expiration date\n\nWhile U.S. ground forces did enter Venezuelan territory in combat capacity and achieved the capture of Maduro, the official statements indicate the operation was primarily for capture and extraction (\"joint military and law enforcement raid\") rather than a sustained effort to seize/hold territory, or establish control of a major population center. The evidence weighs toward this being more of a special operations raid focused on capturing an individual leader, rather than removing the sitting government in the broader sense meant by the proposition, despite the language about overseeing Venezuela post-operation.\n\nBased on the specific carve-out in the proposition that \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO\" and the admitted evidence showing this was primarily a short-term capture operation without indication of lasting territorial control or occupation, I'm submitting my vote.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7df9c03eb22c48ce8bffba53","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The operation was fundamentally a special operations raid to capture Maduro, which falls under the carve-out for 'capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO'. The admitted record shows U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela for approximately two hours to apprehend Maduro, not to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government with lasting effect as defined in the proposition, or establish operational control of a major population center.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-coder-plus","usage":{"input":16161,"output":510,"cacheRead":2560,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19231,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782786507902,"responseId":"gen-1782786508-mndgv8ljcTcj7yUNSfLn"}}
{"type":"message_end","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on the opportunity information, I can see that I have a deliberation opportunity ready for the AAR case. I've received the prompt and have access to the arbitration record consisting of openings, arguments, rebuttals, surrebuttals, closings, and evidence from both plaintiff and defendant.\n\nLet me review the key components of the record to determine the appropriate vote:\n\nThe proposition is whether \"The United States Armed Forces conduct a military operation involving ground troops entering Venezuelan sovereign territory with the objective of seizing or holding territory, removing the sitting government, or establishing operational control of a major population center.\"\n\nThe evidence shows:\n- PX-1 (War.gov/Defense) describes a military operation with ground forces in Caracas that captured Maduro  \n- PX-2 (White House/Rubio) confirms ground forces were present for about two hours for the capture\n- The operation was described as \"not an invasion or extended military operation\"\n- The Defense source states Maduro was \"now out of power\" and US would \"oversee Venezuela\"\n- The event happened on Jan 3, 2026, well before the expiration date\n\nWhile U.S. ground forces did enter Venezuelan territory in combat capacity and achieved the capture of Maduro, the official statements indicate the operation was primarily for capture and extraction (\"joint military and law enforcement raid\") rather than a sustained effort to seize/hold territory, or establish control of a major population center. The evidence weighs toward this being more of a special operations raid focused on capturing an individual leader, rather than removing the sitting government in the broader sense meant by the proposition, despite the language about overseeing Venezuela post-operation.\n\nBased on the specific carve-out in the proposition that \"capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO\" and the admitted evidence showing this was primarily a short-term capture operation without indication of lasting territorial control or occupation, I'm submitting my vote.\n\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7df9c03eb22c48ce8bffba53","name":"mcp","arguments":{"tool":"aar_submit_council_vote","args":"{\"vote\":\"not_demonstrated\",\"rationale\":\"The operation was fundamentally a special operations raid to capture Maduro, which falls under the carve-out for 'capture of a head of state without territorial occupation: NO'. The admitted record shows U.S. ground forces entered Venezuela for approximately two hours to apprehend Maduro, not to seize or hold territory, remove the sitting government with lasting effect as defined in the proposition, or establish operational control of a major population center.\"}"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"qwen/qwen3-coder-plus","usage":{"input":16161,"output":510,"cacheRead":2560,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":19231,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1782786507902,"responseId":"gen-1782786508-mndgv8ljcTcj7yUNSfLn"}}
